# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pyramid-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is a Python web application *framework*.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It is designed to make creating web applications easier.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can get started even if you don't understand it all.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] And when you're ready to do more, Pyramid will be there for you.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Out of the box, Pyramid provides only the core tools needed for nearly all web applications: mapping URLs to code, security, and serving static assets (files like JavaScript and CSS).
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Additional tools provide templating, database integration and more.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] But with Pyramid you can *"pay only for what you eat"*.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is committed to comprehensive and up-to-date documentation.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is designed to be noticeably fast.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is developed conservatively and tested exhaustively.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Our motto is: "If it ain't tested, it's broke".
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] As with Python, the Pyramid software is distributed under a permissive open source license.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In a world filled with web frameworks, why should you choose Pyramid?
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is fully compatible with Python 3.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] If you develop a Pyramid application today, you can rest assured that you'll be able to use the most modern features of your favorite language.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] And in the years to come, you'll continue to be working on a framework that is up-to-date and forward-looking.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The Pyramid community has a strong testing culture and our framework reflects that.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Every release of Pyramid has 100% statement coverage (as measured by coverage) and 95% decision/condition coverage.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] (as measured by instrumental) It is automatically tested using Travis and Jenkins on supported versions of Python after each commit to its GitHub repository.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Official Pyramid add-ons are held to a similar testing standard.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We still find bugs in Pyramid, but we've noticed we find a lot fewer of them while working on projects with a solid testing regime.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The Pyramid documentation is comprehensive.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We strive to keep our narrative documentation both complete and friendly to newcomers.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We also maintain the Pyramid Community Cookbook of recipes demonstrating common scenarios you might face.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Contributions in the form of improvements to our documentation are always appreciated.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] And we always welcome improvements to our official tutorials as well as new contributions to our community maintained tutorials.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It's our goal that no Pyramid question go unanswered.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Whether you ask a question on IRC, on the Pylons-discuss mailing list, or on StackOverflow, you're likely to get a reasonably prompt response.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is also a welcoming, friendly space for newcomers.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We don't tolerate "support trolls" or those who enjoy berating fellow users in our support channels.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We try to keep it well-lit and new-user-friendly.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See also our #pyramid IRC channel, our pylons-discuss mailing list, and Support and Development.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] There are many tools available for web development.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] What would make someone want to use Pyramid instead?
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] With Pyramid you can write very small applications without needing to know a lot.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] And by learning a bit more, you can write very large applications too.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid will allow you to become productive quickly, and will grow with you.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It won't hold you back when your application is small, and it won't get in your way when your application becomes large.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Other application frameworks seem to fall into two non-overlapping categories: those that support "small apps" and those designed for "big apps".
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] We don't believe you should have to make this choice.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can't really know how large your application will become.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You certainly shouldn't have to rewrite a small application in another framework when it gets "too big".
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] A well-designed framework should be able to be good at both.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid provides a set of features that are unique among Python web frameworks.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Others may provide some, but only Pyramid provides them all, in one place, fully documented, and *à la carte* without needing to pay for the whole banquet.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can write a Pyramid application that lives entirely in one Python file.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Such an application is easy to understand since everything is in one place.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It is easy to deploy because you don't need to know much about Python packaging.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid allows you to do almost everything that so-called *microframeworks* can in very similar ways.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See also Creating Your First Pyramid Application.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid allows you to keep your configuration right next to your code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] That way you don't have to switch files to see your configuration.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] However, using Pyramid configuration decorators does not change your code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It remains easy to extend, test, or reuse.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can test your code as if the decorators were not there.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can instruct the framework to ignore some decorators.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can even use an imperative style to write your configuration, skipping decorators entirely.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See also Adding View Configuration Using the @view_config Decorator.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Dynamic web applications produce URLs that can change depending on what you are viewing.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid provides flexible, consistent, easy to use tools for generating URLs.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] When you use these tools to write your application, you can change your configuration without fear of breaking links in your web pages.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Web applications often require JavaScript, CSS, images and other so-called *static assets*.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid provides flexible tools for serving these kinds of files.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can serve them directly from Pyramid, or host them on an external server or CDN (content delivery network).
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Either way, Pyramid can help you to generate URLs so you can change where your files come from without changing any code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid can automatically detect changes you make to template files and code, so your changes are immediately available in your browser.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can debug using plain old `print()` calls, which will display to your console.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid has a debug toolbar that allows you to see information about how your application is working right in your browser.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See configuration, installed packages, SQL queries, logging statements and more.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] When your application has an error, an interactive debugger allows you to poke around from your browser to find out what happened.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] To use the Pyramid debug toolbar, build your project with our cookiecutter.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] When things go wrong, Pyramid gives you powerful ways to fix the problem.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can configure Pyramid to print helpful information to the console.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The `debug_notfound` setting shows information about URLs that aren't matched.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The `debug_authorization` setting provides helpful messages about why you aren't allowed to do what you just tried.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid also has command line tools to help you verify your configuration.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can use `proutes` and `pviews` to inspect how URLs are connected to your application code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid add-ons extend the core of the framework with useful abilities.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] There are add-ons available for your favorite template language, SQL and NoSQL databases, authentication services and more.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Supported Pyramid add-ons are held to the same demanding standards as the framework itself.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You will find them to be fully tested and well documented.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] A fundamental task for any framework is to map URLs to code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In Pyramid, that code is called a view callable.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] View callables can be functions, class methods or even callable class instances.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You are free to choose the approach that best fits your use case.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Regardless of your choice, Pyramid treats them the same.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can change your mind at any time without any penalty.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] There are no artificial distinctions between the various approaches.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In many web frameworks, the static assets required by an application are kept in a globally shared location, "the *static* directory".
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Others use a lookup scheme, like an ordered set of template directories.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Both of these approaches have problems when it comes to customization.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Static assets are located using *asset specifications*, strings that contain reference both to a Python package name and a file or directory name, e.g.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] These specifications are used for templates, JavaScript and CSS, translation files, and any other package-bound static resource.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] By using asset specifications, Pyramid makes it easy to extend your application with other packages without worrying about conflicts.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] What happens if another Pyramid package you are using provides an asset you need to customize?
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Maybe that page template needs better HTML, or you want to update some CSS.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] With asset specifications you can override the assets from other packages using simple wrappers.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Examples: Understanding Asset Specifications and Overriding Assets.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In Pyramid, the job of creating a `Response` belongs to a renderer.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Any templating system—Mako, Chameleon, Jinja2—can be a renderer.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In fact, packages exist for all of these systems.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] But if you'd rather use another, a structured API exists allowing you to create a renderer using your favorite templating system.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can use the templating system *you* understand, not one required by the framework.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] What's more, Pyramid does not make you use a single templating system exclusively.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can use multiple templating systems, even in the same project.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] When you use a renderer with your view callable, you are freed from needing to return a "webby" `Response` object.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Instead your views can return a simple Python dictionary.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid will take care of rendering the information in that dictionary to a `Response` on your behalf.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] As a result, your views are more easily tested, since you don't need to parse HTML to evaluate the results.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid makes it a snap to write unit tests for your views, instead of requiring you to use functional tests.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] By configuring your view to use a renderer, you tell Pyramid to use the `{'a':1}` dictionary and the specified template to render a response on your behalf.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The string passed as `renderer=` above is an asset specification.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Asset specifications are widely used in Pyramid.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] They allow for more reliable customization.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See Find your static assets for more information.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] When writing web applications, it is often important to have your code run at a specific point in the lifecycle of a request.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In Pyramid, you can accomplish this using *subscribers* and *events*.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] For example, you might have a job that needs to be done each time your application handles a new request.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid emits a `NewRequest` event at this point in the request handling lifecycle.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid's event system can be extended as well.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] If you need, you can create events of your own and send them using Pyramid's event system.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Then anyone working with your application can subscribe to your events and coordinate their code with yours.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid ships with internationalization-related features in its core: localization, pluralization, and creating message catalogs from source files and templates.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid allows for a plurality of message catalogs via the use of translation domains.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can create a system that has its own translations without conflict with other translations in other domains.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Example: Internationalization and Localization.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid provides an easy way to *cache* the results of slow or expensive views.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid will automatically add the appropriate `Cache-Control` and `Expires` headers to the response it creates.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] See the `add_view()` method's `http_cache` documentation for more information.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It has been engineered from the ground up for speed.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It only does as much work as absolutely necessary when you ask it to get a job done.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] If you need speed from your application, Pyramid is the right choice for you.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid has built-in support for HTTP sessions, so you can associate data with specific users between requests.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Lots of other frameworks also support sessions.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] But Pyramid allows you to plug in your own custom sessioning system.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] So long as your system conforms to a documented interface, you can drop it in in place of the provided system.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Currently there is a binding package for the third-party Redis sessioning system that does exactly this.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] But if you have a specialized need (perhaps you want to store your session data in MongoDB), you can.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can even switch between implementations without changing your application code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid`provides a way to handle the exceptions your code encounters.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] An :term:`exception view is a special kind of view which is automatically called when a particular exception type arises without being handled by your application.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] For example, you might register an exception view for the `Exception` exception type, which will catch *all* exceptions, and present a pretty "well, this is embarrassing" page.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Or you might choose to register an exception view for only certain application-specific exceptions.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You can make one for when a file is not found, or when the user doesn't have permission to do something.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In the former case, you can show a pretty "Not Found" page; in the latter case you might show a login form.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid has been built with a number of other sophisticated design features that make it adaptable.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid is a member of the collection of software published under the Pylons Project.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pylons software is written by a loose-knit community of contributors.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The Pylons Project website includes details about how Pyramid relates to the Pylons Project.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The first release of Pyramid's predecessor (named `repoze.bfg`) was made in July of 2008.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] At the end of 2010, we changed the name of `repoze.bfg` to Pyramid.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It was merged into the Pylons project as Pyramid in November of that year.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid was inspired by Zope, Pylons (version 1.0), and Django.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] As a result, Pyramid borrows several concepts and features from each, combining them into a unique web framework.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Similar to Zope, Pyramid applications may easily be extended.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] If you work within the constraints of the framework, you can produce applications that can be reused, modified, or extended without needing to modify the original application code.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid also inherits the concepts of traversal and declarative security from Zope.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Similar to Pylons version 1.0, Pyramid is largely free of policy.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] It makes no assertions about which database or template system you should use.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] You are free to use whatever third-party components fit the needs of your specific application.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Pyramid also inherits its approach to URL dispatch from Pylons.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Similar to Django, Pyramid values extensive documentation.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] In addition, the concept of a view is used by Pyramid much as it would be by Django.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] Other Python web frameworks advertise themselves as members of a class of web frameworks named model-view-controller frameworks.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] The authors of Pyramid do not believe that the MVC pattern fits the web particularly well.
[src:pyramid-framework/introduction] However, if this abstraction works for you, Pyramid also generally fits into this class.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Originally called "repoze.bfg", Pyramid gathered attention mostly in the Zope and Plone community as the Open Society Institute's KARL project migrated from Plone to BFG.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] In 2010 it was announced that the Pylons framework will move over to using BFG as a base in version 1.5.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] As a result of the inclusion of BFG into the Pylons project, BFG was renamed Pyramid.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pyramid is a minimalistic, platform-independent web framework.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] It is persistence agnostic and is integrated both with SQL databases via SQLAlchemy and with the Zope Object Database, as well as other NoSQL databases, such as CouchDB.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pyramid allows developers to define routes using regular expressions that map to objects.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Like its fellow framework Zope, Pyramid also allows hierarchical object traversal, where each part of a URL is an object containing other objects, in a way that is similar to folders in a filesystem.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pylons is well known for having a near-complete stack of third-party tools, eschewing the "not-invented-here" phenomenon.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] The official installation method of Pylons is through EasyInstall via the Python Package Index (PyPI), and most of the additional tools are typically installed the same way.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] EasyInstall also handles package dependencies when relevant.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Some distributions could also package Pylons and Paste, but it is likely that any distribution's packages would lag the official distribution.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pylons may also be installed by hand by renaming its .egg file to .zip and extracting the contents.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Paste is used for project setup, testing, and deployment.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Using the common INI configuration format, Paste allows for multiple "profiles", so that developers can run development and deployment setups from the same codebase without revealing sensitive parts of Pylons, such as the interactive debugger, to production users.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Currently the only widely used URL dispatcher for Pylons is Routes, a Python reimplementation of Ruby on Rails' URL dispatching, although any WSGI-compatible URL dispatcher can be used.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] While Routes is a separate library, it was developed for use in Pylons and its development remains closely in sync with Pylons.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Another piece of Rails adapted for Pylons is WebHelpers, which provides URL mapping based on the Routes configuration.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] WebHelpers also provides some utility functions for generating JavaScript code making use of the script.aculo.us and Prototype libraries.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] FormEncode and FormBuild are used for HTML form validation and generation; there has been some use of Mako for form generation using Mako's inheritance model.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Myghty was the default Pylons templating language, but as of version 0.9.6 it has been replaced by Mako.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Both templating languages are text-based (as opposed to XML-based), and support includes, inheritance and embedding arbitrary Python code.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Because of Pylons' loosely coupled layers, other templating languages can be used as well.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Genshi, an XML-based templating language, can be used in lieu of either Mako or Myghty.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Both SQLObject and SQLAlchemy are known to be used.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pylons has developed into the Pylons Project, and the old code from Pylons 1.0 is now in maintenance-only mode.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] However, pursuant to the project's merger with repoze.bfg since November 2010, newer versions of Pylons are actually different from the original Pylons 1.0.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] Pylons developers initially planned to rewrite certain portions of the code, but they observed that the new code was approximating repoze.bfg, which led to the merger of Pylons and repoze.bfg.
[src:pyramid-framework/pylons-project] This led to repoze.bfg (a part of the Repoze Python-based web framework) to become rebranded and relaunched as the Pyramid web framework.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:pyramid-framework/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:pyramid-framework/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] The **Web Server Gateway Interface** (**WSGI**, pronounced *whiskey* or *WIZ-ghee*) is a simple calling convention for web servers to forward requests to web applications or frameworks written in the Python programming language.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] The current version of WSGI, version 1.0.1, is specified in Python Enhancement Proposal (PEP) 3333.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was originally specified as PEP-333 in 2003.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] PEP-3333, published in 2010, updates the specification for Python 3.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] In 2003, Python web frameworks were typically written against only CGI, FastCGI, mod_python, or some other custom API of a specific web server.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was thus created as an implementation-neutral interface between web servers and web applications or frameworks to promote common ground for portable web application development.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] Between the server and the application, there may be one or more *WSGI middleware components*, which implement both sides of the API, typically in Python code.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI does not specify how the Python interpreter should be started, nor how the application object should be loaded or configured, and different frameworks and webservers achieve this in different ways.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] A full example of a WSGI network server is outside the scope of this article.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] Below is a sketch of how one would call a WSGI application and retrieve its HTTP status line, response headers, and response body, as Python objects.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] Details of how to construct the `environ` dict have been omitted.
[src:pyramid-framework/web-server-gateway-interface] Currently wrappers are available for FastCGI, CGI, SCGI, AJP (using flup), twisted.web, Apache (using mod_wsgi or mod_python), Nginx (using ngx_http_uwsgi_module), Nginx Unit (using the Python language module), and Microsoft IIS (using WFastCGI, isapi-wsgi, PyISAPIe, or an ASP gateway).
